Package: QuantFit
Title: Checking Quantitative Structure in Item Response Data
Version: 0.2.2
Authors@R: c(
    person("Josh", "McGrane", email = "drjoshmcgrane@gmail.com",
           role = c("aut", "cre")),
    person("Ben", "Domingue", email = "ben.domingue@gmail.com",
           role = "aut", comment = "Author of the original ConjointChecks package"),
    person("Liam", "Fox", role = "ctb"),
    person("Vithor", "Franco", role = "ctb"))
Description: Tools for empirically testing whether psychological and
    educational item response data (dichotomous or polytomous) support a
    quantitative interpretation of the latent variable. Implements three
    complementary approaches:
    (1) Bayesian checks of the single, double, and triple cancellation
    axioms of additive conjoint measurement, extending the ConjointChecks
    package of Domingue (2014) <doi:10.1007/s11336-013-9342-4>; the
    parametric bootstrap calibration of these axiom checks follows
    Student & Read (2025) <doi:10.3758/s13428-025-02844-7>;
    (2) the Bayesian omnibus test of additive conjoint measurement axioms
    using synthetic likelihood of Karabatsos (2018)
    <doi:10.1007/s11336-017-9581-x>; and
    (3) the latent structure model selection framework of Torres Irribarra
    & Diakow, comparing six latent structure models (Unconstrained Latent
    Class, Class Monotonicity, Invariant Item Ordering, Double
    Monotonicity, Latent Class Rasch, and Rasch Model) to determine
    whether data support classificatory, ordinal, or quantitative
    interpretations.
